05684nam a22006615i 9780228007456DE-B159720230529094047.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230529t20212021xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97802280074567 a10.1515/97802280074562doi  a(DE-B1597)657394  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aJC423b.C667 2021 7aPOL0090002bisacsh04a321.822300aConstitutional Politics in Multinational Democracies /ced. by André Lecours, Guy Laforest, Nikola Brassard-Dion. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[2021] 4c©2021  a1 online resource :b7 tables, 1 diagram  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aDemocracy, Diversity, and Citizen Engagement Series00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tFigures and Tables -- tConstitutional Politics in Multinational Democracies -- tWhat’s the Deal? Canada’s Constitutional Relationship with the Métis Nation -- tResponding to Secession Referenda: Constitutional and Quasi-constitutional Change in Quebec and Scotland -- tEmbedded Independence: Self-Government and Interdependence in the Scottish National Movement -- tFlemish Nationalism and the Left-Right Divide: Consequences for Constitutional Politics in Belgium -- tThe Legitimacy-Legality Constitutional Paradox in Multinational Democracies and the Constitutional Origins of Sub-State Party System Realignments -- tBosnia and Herzegovina: Constitutional Politics in a “State of Minorities” -- tThe Nature, Actors, and Process of Constitutional Politics -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aConstitutional politics is exceptionally intense and unpredictable. It involves negotiations over the very nature of the state and the implications of self- determination. Multinational democracies face pressing challenges to the existing order because they are composed of communities with distinct cultures, histories, and aspirations, striving to coexist under mutually agreed-upon terms. Conflict over the recognition of these multiple identities and the distribution of power and resources is inevitable and, indeed, part of what defines democratic life in multinational societies.In Constitutional Politics in Multinational Democracies André Lecours, Nikola Brassard-Dion, and Guy Laforest bring together experts on multinational democracies to analyze the claims of minority nations about their political future and the responses they elicit through constitutional politics. Essays focus on the nature of these states and the actors and political process within them. This framework allows for a multidimensional examination of crucial political periods in these democracies by assessing what constitutional politics is, who is involved in it, and how it happens. Case studies include Catalonia and Spain, Puerto Rico and the United States, Scotland and the United Kingdom, Belgium, Bosnia and Herzegovina, and Quebec and the Métis People in Canada.Theoretically significant and empirically rich, Constitutional Politics in Multinational Democracies is a necessary read for any student of multinationalism.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aComparative governmentvCase studies. 0aConstitutional historyvCase studies. 0aDemocracyvCase studies. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Comparative Politics.2bisacsh1 aAdam, Elisenda Casanas, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAnderson, Paul, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrassard-Dion, Nikola, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrassard-Dion, Nikola, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aDubois, Janique, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKeil, Soere